 and Debate among Jews of the Middle Ages in Areas Under Muslim Rule -- tThe Renaissance and Enlightenment Accelerate the Secularisation Process in Judaism as Well, Following Spinoza -- tThe Distinct Character of Jewish Apikorsim – Whose Lives and Education are Influenced by Jewish National Culture -- tA-theistic and Epicurean Philosophies Develop in the Middle of the First Millennium BCE -- tEpicureanism Spread throughout the Mediterranean Basin in the Hellenistic Period -- tThe Difference between Epicureanism and the Platonism that Prevailed at the Schools in Epicurus’ Time -- tCommitment to the Principles of Justice and Moral Values that Stem from the Epicurean Belief that Man’s Ultimate Goal is the Improvement of Life and the Multiplication and Refinement of its Pleasures -- tIn the Late Middle Ages, Renaissance and Age of Enlightenment - Man, His Pleasures and His Happiness Are Once Again the Ultimate Goal of Morality -- tPrevailing Epicurean Ideas in the Age of Enlightenment: Pursuit of Happiness, Unity of Body and Soul, Existence of a Single World, Motion of Particles in Matter -- tEpicurean Principles Guide the Actions of Individuals in Contemporary Western Culture; and the Ways in which they Approach the Contrasts and Interdependence of the Free-Market Economy and the Welfare State -- tThe First Jewish Apikoros – Ninth Century Freethinker Hiwi al-Balkhi, Influenced by the Islamic Rationalist Movements -- tThe Subjects of Hiwi’s Criticism: Biblical Criticism, the Relationship between God and the World, God’s Corporeality, Miracles, the Religious Precepts, Punishment and Reward, the World to Come0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book describes the influence of Epicurus on Judaism. Judaism is the only national culture which has adopted the name of this Greek philosopher, using it as a term designating Jews who believe in freedom to choose their way of life, without obligation to obey religious precepts. Today, most Jews live as "Apikorsim". The heresy implicit in the denial of the existence of a personal God includes a denial of belief in life after death. Apikorsim believe that the purpose of life and of morality is found in striving for happiness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertGorgias Press Backlist eBook-Package 2001-2015z978311066303740uhttps://doi.org/10.31826/978146321931440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781463219314423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781463219314/original  a978-3-11-066303-7  Gorgias Press Backlist eBook-Package 2001-2015c2001d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK